  "prompt": "EBITDA cash flow?",
  "response": "EBITDA and cash flow are related but distinct financial metrics:\n\nEBITDA (Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization):\n- Measures a company's operating performance\n- Calculated by adding back interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization to net income\n- Shows profitability before accounting for financial and accounting decisions\n- Helps compare companies across different industries\n\nCash Flow:\n- Tracks actual cash moving in and out of a business\n- Typically measured through Cash Flow Statement\n- Shows liquidity and ability to pay expenses and generate value\n- Includes operating, investing, and financing cash flows\n\nKey differences:\n- EBITDA is an earnings metric\n- Cash flow reflects actual cash movements\n- EBITDA doesn't directly equal cash flow\n- Conversion of EBITDA to cash flow requires adjusting for working capital changes, capital expenditures, etc.\n\nWhile related, they provide different insights into a company's financial health and performance.",
